\begin_layout Subsection
Product Topology aside
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 a topological space.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and any open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset Y$
\end_inset

, define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\left(x,U\right)=\left\{ f\in Y^{X};f\left(x\right)\in U\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

This is a set of functions! And the universal quantifier is over 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
product topology
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{X}$
\end_inset

 is the topology generated by the subbasis consisting of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ S\right\} $
\end_inset

 are subbasis not a basis.
 To form basic sets you take finite intersections of subbasic sets (and
 then to form sets in the topology you take arbitrary unions of basic sets).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fact:sufbasictop"

\end_inset

It is sufficient to only consider basis sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 I.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ S\left(x,U\right);x\in X,U\in\tau\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a basis for the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, is a subbasis for the product topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{X}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition coincides with the product topology on the Cartesian product
 of two topological spaces (hence the name)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
If 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a topological space, then the product 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\times Y$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as a function fome 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{X}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset Y$
\end_inset

 is open, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(1,U\right)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that map 1 to an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and map 2 to some element of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly then 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(1,U\right)$
\end_inset

 can identified with all tuples 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\left(1,U\right)\cong U\times Y
\]

\end_inset

Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\left(2,U\right)\cong Y\times U
\]

\end_inset

These sets form a subbasis for the product topology on the Cartesian product
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\times Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\twonotes$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that we've identified 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 can we identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 with some 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Omega}$
\end_inset

? Recall that the topological 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra on a set is just the collection of all open subsets of that set.
 Hence the sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \omega_{X};\omega_{X}\left(t_{1}\right)\in B_{1},\dots,\omega_{X}\left(t_{k}\right)\in B_{k}\right\} ,\ B\in\mathcal{B}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{X}\left(t\right)=X_{\omega}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, generate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Omega}$
\end_inset

.
 Why? The sets 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\left(t,B\right)=\left\{ \omega_{X}\in\tilde{\Omega}=\left(\mathbb{R}^{n}\right)^{T};\omega_{X}\left(t\right)\in B\right\} ,\:B\in\mathcal{B}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

form a subbasis for the product topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Omega}$
\end_inset

