\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 (is the basis for a topology also the generator for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra for the topological 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra?).
 
\series bold
Hence
\series default
 it's reasonable to say that a stochastic process is a probability measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{P}$
\end_inset

 on the measurable space
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tilde{\Omega}=\left(\mathbb{R}^{n}\right)^{T},\tilde{\mathcal{F}}\right)$
\end_inset

, called the 
\emph on
law
\emph default
 
\emph on
of the process
\emph default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{X}:\Omega\rightarrow\tilde{\Omega}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the process, defined by currying 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t,\omega\right)=X_{t}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\Phi_{X}\left(\cdot\right)\right)\left(t\right)=X\left(t,\cdot\right)=X_{t}\left(\cdot\right)
\]

\end_inset

then the law
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
pushforward
\emph default
 of the measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{X}\coloneqq\left(\Phi_{X}\right)_{*}\left(P\right)=P\circ\Phi_{X}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The process also induces induces a set of measures on its range
